### Manage Yards \- Ready

2 pages \- Manage Yards page & Yard Builder page \+ a Create New Yard flow

* Manage Yards page  
  * Capacity summary cards, similar to the Yard Overview on the Dashboard  
    * Different metrics though \-   
      * \# of parking spaces  
      * \# of sections  
      * \# of doors   
    * Yard Name, address, Yard status  
    * Edit Layout button \> Yard Builder page   
    * Copy Layout button \> starts Create Yard flow \> Yard Builder page (but layout is already setup)   
  * Search bar, same as Dashboard \- by name or address  
  * \+ Create New Yard button \> starts Create Yard flow \> Yard Builder page  
* Create Yard Flow  
  * Click \+ Create New Yard OR Copy Layout icon   
  * Navigates to new page or modal with the following  
    * 1st \- ask if user wants to use an existing Org Profile or Create a new one  
      * If existing Org profile \- provide user with a Search bar to search existing Orgs.  User selects one \> proceed to step 2  
      * If new Org profile \- proceed to step 2  
    * 2nd \- Input Org Details \- Can use existing “Add Organization” modal   
      * If existing Org profile \- all fields will be auto-populated already.  The bottom right button will instead say “Confirm”   
        * If Org is not already categorized as a Yard, then add  
      * If new org profile \- user fills out required fields at a minimum (just name and address) and clicks “Create”   
    * 3rd \- navigate to Yard Builder page

![][image1]

* Yard Builder page  
  * Creating a Yard  
    * Experience will be similar to Figma and/or LucidChart where a user can   
      * Drag/drop elements from the sidebar into the Layout Editor  
      * Resize / remove elements once placed in the Layout Editor  
      * ‘Label’ elements with text to give them a name   
    * Elements  
      * Element Types  
        * Parking space   
          * Represents a container, chassis, or trailer (or potentially the parking for a dock door)  
          * Default format is a vertical rectangle   
        * Section (No assigned spots)   
          * Default format is a large square, roughly the size of 4 parking spots x 2 parking spots   
          * Area available for parking, but no specific spot numbers will be assigned  
          * Request user to input max count of equipment that can be parked in that section   
        * Landmark  
          * Any area where equipment cannot be parked, i.e. Office, Warehouse, Truck Parking, etc  
          * Default format is a square roughly twice the width of a parking space   
        * Gate  
          * This is also a non-parkable area, but is good to give them this specific option from the building toolbar to encourage the user to add their Gate(s) to the layout as it can potentially be helpful info to the Dispatch team when giving drivers instructions  
          * Default format is a vertical rectangle, slightly larger than a parking space   
      * Editing elements  
        * Double click to update name  
        * Click corner and drag to resize  
        * Click and drag to change location   
        * Icon to rotate 45 degrees  
        * Single click on element to ‘select’  
          * If one element is selected hold CTRL and click on other elements to select multiple elements at once  
      * When 1 or more elements are select \> “Action” bar appears at the bottom (similar to the bar at the bottom of the Dispatch board when a Load is selected)   
        * Copy  
          * Copies the selected element(s) to the users clipboard  
        * Add Multiple (not available if more than 1 element is selected)   
          * Options  
            * Copy \_\_\_ to the right  
            * Copy \_\_\_ to the left  
            * Copy \_\_\_ below  
            * Copy \_\_\_ above  
            * Button: “Add Elements”  
          * UI similar to the Edit Dates button in the Dispatch board.  Except user can enter a quantity in 1 or multiple of the fields.  Then when the click “Add Elements”, that \# of elements of the same type and size will be added to the Layout in the specified locations (with a slight amount of spacing between each)   
          * ![][image2]  
        * Assign to Section (only available if only Parking Spaces are selected)   
          * “Create Section” Modal   
            * “Section Name (ex. “A” or “Overflow”)”: \_\_\_\_  
            * “Update Spot Numbers in Section?” (checkbox)   
              * If checked, add/override labels for the selected elements  
              * Naming convention is “\[Section Name\] \- \[number value\]”   
              * The number value is an integer.  The numbering will start at 1 from the top left corner, then increase the number moving to the right ending at the right-most selected element.  If there are selected elements below, continue numbering starting from the left of the next row.    
            * Save Button   
        * Assign Spot Numbers (only available if only Parking Spaces are selected and all are in the same section)   
          * Ask user “Begin with number \_\_\_” (only integers allowed)   
          * User inputs value and clicks Save  
          * System adds/overrides labels on the selected elements.  Follow the same logic as when assigning spot numbers in the Section Assignment flow, but can start with the number the user specifies  
          * If no section assigned, text will just show “Spot 1, Spot 2, etc)    
        * Mark Staging  
          * “Staging” will be a TRUE/FALSE field associated with every Spot and Section.    
          * Default value is FALSE  
          * Clicking on this edit option, the user is asked “Mark the selected locations as staging areas?” and user must select Yes or No  
            * Yes will update all selected locations to Staging \= TRUE  
            * No will update all selected locations to Staging \= FALSE  
        * Delete  
          * Removes selected elements from the layout  
    * Also provide a summary that displays counts of   
      * Sections  
      * Parking Spaces  
      * Gates  
      * Dock Doors  
      * Top Loaders  
      * Yard Goats  
  * Other functions  
    * Update Status: Active, Inactive  
    * Cancel   
      * If they Click ‘Cancel’ and any changes have been made to the format, provide a popup that states “If you Cancel, you will lose all updates made on this page.  Are you sure you would like to Cancel?”  Options are “Stay on page” and “Leave page without saving”  
    * Save   
      * Save changes to the yard format  
      * This may update total yard capacity and the format displayed in the Current Inventory View  
    * Delete Yard (this is only available if the Yard has never had any Inventory or Gate Transactions before- otherwise they would change status to Inactive instead)   
    * Download  
      * This will be an image file (pdf, jpeg, etc)   
  * Editing a Yard when equipment is currently allocated   
    * If a Yard is currently in use and has inventory assigned to spots, the user will be limited in what they can edit.  However, provide them this info & option at the top  
      * “Editing functions are limited as there is currently inventory assigned to Spaces in this Yard.  If you would like full editing functionality, check this box and click Confirm.  Warning: this will update the Location of all current inventory to “Unassigned”. “  
        * A checkbox will be displayed   
        * If user checks the box, a Confirm button will appear  
        * If the user clicks Confirm, a modal will popup that says “Are you sure you want to move all inventory to an Unassigned location?”  
          * Options: Cancel, Confirm  
          * “Cancel” will uncheck the box and not change anything  
          * “Confirm” will update the current location of all inventory currently in the yard to Unassigned   
    * Otherwise, the only editing functionality allowed on this page is to   
      * Re-name / label elements  
        * If any Parking Spaces or Sections are re-named, the spot locations displayed elsewhere in the YMS (and TMS) will be updated accordingly once changes are Saved  
      * Add, remove, or adjust non-parking space elements 

Expected User Groups

* Yard Manager only

### Current Inventory \- Ready  

User navigates here by clicking on a Yard Card from the Dashboard page 

2 pages, but with the same information, just different views of it: Current inventory \- Map view and List view 

* List View  
  * Lists equipment currently in the yard in a ‘table-like’ format  
    * Sorting and filtering enabled in each column except  
      * time related columns would only have sorting  
      * Equipment \# would be a search bar instead   
  * Each row represents a piece of equipment \- chassis, container, or trailer  
  * Columns  
    * Checked In At (timestamp of when it entered the yard, cannot be edited)   
    * Dwell time (In days.  If less than 24 hours, then in hours)   
    * Equipment \# \- if a mounted container, will have 2 values \- “\[container number\] / \[chassis number\]”  
    * Equipment Type (values \= Container, Chassis, Trailer)   
    * Loaded / Empty (values \= Loaded, Empty)  
      * Will be null for chassis  
    * Location (if none, put ‘unassigned’)   
      * Can be a specific spot \#, section name, or ‘unassigned‘  
    * Status (values \= wheeled, grounded, stacked)   
      * Will be NA for trailers  
      * Containers can be any value  
      * Chassis can be grounded or stacked  
    * Customer  
    * Destination / Delivery Location  (full only)   
    * Destination distance (in miles) (full only)   
    * Scheduled Delivery Date (full only)   
    * FTE (Per Diem LFD)   
    * Weight (full only)  
    * Flags \- multiple values can apply.  Options are  
      * Overweight \- pulled from Load data (for Loaded containers only)   
      * Long Distance \- pulled from routing data (for Loaded containers only, distance from pickup to delivery)   
      * Damaged \- can be applied manually   
      * Load Routing Incorrect (auto applied when the Current Location on the Load is not the same Org as the current Yard)   
      * Not found in TMS (Container only)   
    * Notes \- open entry   
  * Edit icon \- when clicked \- modal to Edit Inventory pops up.  User can edit the following  
    * Equipment \#  
    * Equipment Type (dropdown)  
    * Loaded/Empty (dropdown)  
    * Location   
      * Can specify a spot number, a section, or mark unassigned  
      * If spot number is selected, can also mark as  ‘Stacked” which will allow them to add a letter at the end of the spot \#   
        * This will flag the spot as a “Stack” and inventory will increase so that this 1 spot \= 4 spaces   
    * Status  (dropdown)  
    * Flags \- add/remove Damaged flag only  
    * Notes  
    * Buttons to   
      * Cancel  
      * Save  
      * “Create Yard Move” which opens “Create Yard Move” modal with the equipment number(s) pre-populated   
* Map View  
  * Essentially what you would see in the Yard Builder page, but just the layout itself without the ‘building’ options/functions   
  * Per spot, if the spot is occupied, display the Equipment number(s) and the icons for any flags present   
  * If equipment is ‘unassigned’ to a spot, we should have a section off to the side that says “Unassigned Equipment”   
  * Clicking on a piece of equipment will display a modal with all the info present in the List View \+ Edit button which then enables the user to click into the Edit-able fields (same fields as List view)  
  * Clicking on a Section with assigned equipment will bring up a modal that lists all assigned inventory.  Clicking on one of the listed equipment will open the associated Inventory Details modal  
  * Searching / filtering  
    * Results are highlighted in the map   
    * Search by Equipment \#   
    * Filter button  
      * Equipment Type  
      * Loaded / Empty  
      * Status (Equipment)  
      * Customer  
      * Flags  
      * Date Arrived (on, before, after, between)  
* Other actions available  
  * Zoom In / Zoom Out  
  * Download   
    * On List, download as CSV, excel or google sheet  
    * On Map, download as image file (pdf, jpeg, etc) 

Expected user groups \- All

* Yard Staff (Manager, Hostlers)   
* Ops Teams (Customer Success, Dispatch, Equipment Teams) \- view only  
* Leadership

### Yard Moves \- Ready

1 page for now \- In-Yard Moves (Inbound/Outbound Plan and Dock Moves in later milestones)   
2 flows \- Create/Edit Yard Move and  Complete Yard Move

* In-Yard Moves  
  * List of Moves.  Columns per row  
    * (If more than one Yard exists) Yard Name  
    * Move Type (values \= Reposition, Ground, Mount, Stack, Unstack, Flip)  
    * Equipment Type (chassis, container, trailer, tractor) \- Available Move Types per equipment Type:   
      * Reposition \- all  
      * Stack or Unstack \- container or chassis   
      * Mount, Ground or Flip \- container only  
    * Equipment \#  
    * From   
    * To   
      * If Reposition, Ground, Stack, or Unstack \- value \= location / section or unassigned  
      * If Mount or Flip, value \= chassis \#  
    * Priority   
    * Status   
    * Assigned to  
      * If unassigned, show “Assign” button  
      * Clicking Assign will display a list of Yard Managers and Yard Hostlers for that yard for the user to select from  
    * Scheduled pickup time  
      * If present on Load, same logic as in Inbound/Outbound plan   
    * Created by (values \= username or ‘recommendation’)   
    * If not in Done status \- Start button \> begins Complete Yard Move flow  
    * Edit icon  
      * Opens “Edit Yard Move’ modal which is the same as Create Yard Move modal, but user can adjust values   
    * Trash can icon to Delete Move \- will ask user if they are sure they want toe Delete   
  * Other functions   
    * Create Move button from the Yard Moves list page OR from the Equipment Details modal in the Current Inventory page \> opens Create Yard Move modal  
    * Create Yard Move flow  
      * Click Create Move button  
      * Create Move modal pops up   
      * Fields  
        * Equipment \#   
          * Required Field  
        * Equipment Type  
          * Options: Container \#, Chassis \#, Trailer \#, Tractor \#  
        * Move Type:   
          * For MVP, only one type required= Reposition   
          * Then in M1, we will support Top Loader Moves so additional types are available: Ground, Mount, Stack, Unstack, Flip  
        * From  
          * Value \= Spot \#, Section, or Unassigned  
        * To  
          * Value \= Spot \#, Section, or Unassigned  
        * Priority  
          * Values \= Normal, High, Urgent  
          * Default \= Normal  
        * Status  
          * Values \=  To Do, In Progress, Done  
          * Default \= To Do  
          * No state machine required, any status value can be changed to any other status value  
        * Assigned To  
          * Select from yard staff users  
          * Default to Unassigned/null   
          * Value not required to Save Move or Complete Move  
        * Note \- If user navigates here from the Equipment Details modal, the following fields are auto-populated based on the what the Equipment Details they were viewing / triggered the Create  Move from   
          * Equipment \#  
          * Equipment Type  
          * From  
    * Edit Yard Move flow  
      * Click “Edit” on an existing Move  
      * The same modal from Create Move pops up,  but says “Edit Yard Move” instead and all fields are already populated  
    * Complete Move flow  
      * From the Yard Moves list page, user clicks “Start Move”   
        * Move status to In Progress  
      * Display a modal that has all the same info as the Create/Edit Move modal  
      * Button Options  
        * Cancel (if clicked, status move back to To Do)  
        * Complete  
          * If clicked and all fields are populated, close modal and move status to Done  
          * If clicked and the “To” field still \= Unassigned, ask the user “A new location has not been assigned, are you sure you would like to mark this Complete?”  
            * If No, they stay on In Progress modal  
            * If Yes, status moves to Done and To value remains as Unassigned   
    * Download button (csv, excel, google sheet) 

Expected user groups:

* Yard Staff (Manager, Hostlers)   
* Other misc users, maybe some Ops groups

### Gate Transactions \- Ready

One ‘list’ page that has search and filter functionality 

* Lists out all recorded gate transactions \-   
  * It will be very similar to the current inventory page, just different columns and no Edit functions    
  * Since it will technically list all transactions that ever occurred at the yard, by default, set the date filter to ‘in the last 30 days/1 month’ so it doesn’t take forever to load  
* Columns  
  * Transaction Timestamp  
  * Transaction Type \- values \= gate in, gate out   
  * Equipment \# \- if a mounted container, will have 2 values \- “\[container number\] / \[chassis number\]”  
  * Equipment Type (values \= Container, Chassis Only, Trailer, Tractor)   
  * Loaded / Empty (values \= Loaded, Empty)  
    * Will be null for chassis  
  * Driver First Name  
  * Driver Last Name  
  * Truck Plate \#  
* Other functions  
  * All columns have sort / filter functions  
    * Sort only on needed on Timestamp and Equipment \# columns  
  * Search bar \- equipment \#  
  * Date filter next to Search bar  
    * Options: on, after, before, between \[select date or date range\]  
    * By default set value to ‘between’ \[30 days ago\] \- \[current date\]  
  * Download \-   
    * csv, excel, or google sheet  
    * The export will contain all transactions that match the filter criteria currently set

### Yard Check \- Ready 

Yard Check page and Yard Check Flow

* Yard Check page  
  * If user has access to more than 1 yard, filter cards at the top (per yard)   
  * Filter options   
    * Date Range (on, before, after, between // default to past 30 days)   
    * Yard Check status   
  * Yard Check List \- displays all past Yard Checks   
    * Yard Name  
    * Started At   
    * Check Type  
    * Status (Not Started, In Progress, Complete)   
      * Default when Check is created \= Not Started  
      * Once an update is made to one spot (confirmed or issue reported), status \= In Progress

  * Clicking on a specific yard check \- takes user to final results of the selected yard check.  Option to view either Map or List view   
  * Button to “Start Yard Check” \> Yard Check flow

  * Start Yard Check modal pops up   
    * If user has access to more than 1 Yard, display dropdown to select Yard  
    * Check Type  
      * Full Yard Check (default selection)   
      * Section Check   
        * If selected, user is presented with list of Sections in that Yard  
    * Buttons: Cancel, Save, or Save & Start  
  * User is taken to the Map view of Current Inventory (but with option to see List View)   
    * By default the spot or row has a light gray background  
    * Display spot \# and any equipment \#(s) currently assigned to the spot

        * Location   
        * Equipment type  
        * Equipment \#s    
        * Status (Pending, Confirmed, or Issue Reported)   
        * Issue Type   
    * On each parking spot, there are 2 buttons: green check mark, and red exclamation mark.  (In the List view, these buttons would exist in each row)   
      * Clicking the Green check mark, Status \= Confirmed.  Spot/row turns a light green background   
      * Clicking the Red exclamation mark, Status \= Issue Reported  \> Report Issue modal pops up.

          * Equipment Damaged  
            * If selected, display optional “Notes” field  
          * Spot is empty:  If selected, user has 2 options (select 1\) \-

            * Select equipment type  
            * Enter equipment \# (s)

              * If Yes, prompt user to select location   
              * If No, set location to Not Found  
        * Spot / row is highlighted light yellow

          

    * Reported Issues Summary  
      * Right hand slider with 2 tabs  
        * “Equipment Not Found”.  Displays summary cards that include the following details   
          * Expected Location  
          * Equipment Type  
          * Equipment \#(s)   
        * “Reported Issues”.  Displays summary cards that include the following details  
          * Issue Type: Spot is Empty, Found Other Equipment  
          * Original Equipment Type  
          * Original Equipment \#(s)   
          * Original Expected Location   
          * New location   
          * New Equipment \#(s)

### Mobile Requirements \- Ready 

* All pages need to be Mobile friendly except for Yard Builder.  For now Yard Builder can be desktop only  
* Support all screen size \- Phones & Tablets, etc  
* Ensure there is dynamic resizing, especially on the Map View as there will be a lot of zooming in / zooming out  
* Need a mobile friendly navigation method \- can always display the 3-line Menu icon on the top left or something which pulls out a slider when clicked on that lists the main navigation tabs/pages   
* Current Inventory \- Map View   
  * Display Map section & header summary (open, reserved, outbound, etc) only by default.    
  * So don’t display the left or right sliders when page is first opened, instead provide easily visible buttons for “List View”, “Inbound/Outbound Summary”, and “Unassigned Equipment”   
    * Since users can turn a mobile screen, display the equipment number vertically to reduce horizontal space per spot.  Auto resize the elements in the map to reduce white space   
    * Inbound/Outbound Summary will bring up a page that only displays the summary info that is on the Browser view.  Provide back or X button to navigate back to Map

### Inbound / Outbound Plan \- Ready {#inbound-/-outbound-plan---ready}

* A ‘plan’ record is essentially an expected upcoming Gate Transaction estimated based on Load Routing (locations and appointments) in the TMS.  ‘  
  * The Inbound Plan lists what inventory is scheduled to arrive to the Yard  
    * YMS users will reference this to ensure there are enough available spaces and potentially pre-assign Inventory to spots   
  * The Outbound Plan lists what inventory is scheduled to depart the Yard  
    * TMS users will reference this ensure any required prep-work is completed on time (staging, unstacking, mounting, etc)   
* Identifying when a ‘plan’ record should be recorded based on the Load/Move  
  * Note \- a ‘plan’ record is associated to an individual routing event from the Load.  However, the appointments and locations of the other events in the *same* Move will potentially impact the ‘plan’ record  
  * Criteria to ID from the Load routing Inbound Loaded  
    * Import Container AND   
      * Routing event \= Drop at \[YMS Yard\]   
        * This Drop event occurs between Pickup and Delivery   
      * OR Export Container AND  
        * Routing event \= Drop at \[YMS Yard\]   
        * This Drop event occurs between Delivery and Return  
    * Outbound Loaded  
      * Import Container AND   
        * Routing event \= Hook at \[YMS Yard\]   
        * This Hook event occurs between Pickup and Delivery   
      * OR Export Container AND  
        * Routing event \= Hook at \[YMS Yard\]   
        * This Hook event occurs between Delivery and Return  
    * Inbound Empty  
      * Import Container AND   
        * Routing event \= Drop at \[YMS Yard\]   
        * This Drop event occurs between Delivery and Return  
      * OR Export Container AND  
        * Routing event \= Drop at \[YMS Yard\]   
        * This Drop event occurs between Pickup and Delivery   
    * Outbound Empty  
      * Import Container AND   
        * Routing event \= Hook at \[YMS Yard\]   
        * This Hook event occurs between Delivery and Return  
      * OR Export Container AND  
        * Routing event \= Hook at \[YMS Yard\]   
        * This Drop event occurs between Pickup and Delivery  
    * Note, creation of an Outbound plan record can be the start of the funnel to identify and create Recommended In-Yard Moves   
  * Create a ‘plan’ record  
    * Scenario 1 \- appt on the Yard Routing Event is updated  
      * GIVEN a Routing Event on a Load has been identified as a ‘potential plan’ based on the above criteria,  
      * WHEN an appointment is added to that routing event   
      * THEN create an inbound/outbound record with Expected Time \= the entered appt time   
    * Scenario 2 \- appt on a Routing Event in the same Move as the Yard Routing Event is updated   
      * GIVEN a Routing Event on a Load has been identified as a ‘potential plan’ based on the above criteria  
      * AND the appt on the Yard Routing Event is null  
      * WHEN an appointment is added to a routing event that is in the same Move as the Yard Routing Event  
      * THEN calculate the travel time between the Yard Routing event and the updated Routing event to estimate when the Driver is expected to arrive at the Yard  
      * AND create an inbound/outbound record with Expected Time \= the estimated driver arrival time  
    * Once a ‘plan’ record is created for an individual Yard Routing Event, if either of the 2 above scenarios occur again (perhaps by a user updating the Routing Event appt), it will not create a new record, but update the existing one instead   
  * Edit a ‘plan’ record  
    * Scenario 1 \- An Appt time changes in the Move   
      * IF the appt time on the Yard Routing Event is changed , update the Expected Time value on the ‘plan’ record  
      * IF the appt time on the Yard Routing event is null and an appt time for a Routing Event in the same Move is changed, re-calculate the estimated Driver arrival time and update the Expected Time value on the ‘plan’ record   
      * Note \- If an appt time is entered on both the Yard Routing Event and other Events in the Move, prioritize the appt time of the Yard Routing Event (disregard changes to other appts in the Move)   
    * Scenario 2 \- Location of a different routing Event in the Move changes  
      * IF the appt time on the Yard Routing event is null and the location for a Routing Event in the same Move is changed, re-calculate the estimated Driver arrival time and update the Expected Time value on the ‘plan’ record   
  * Delete a ‘plan’ record  
    * Location of the Yard Routing Event changes  
    * Move with the Yard Routing Event is deleted   
    * The associated Load is Completed  
    * The associated Load is Deleted   
    * User manually selects Delete from the YMS inbound/outbound plan page  
  * Complete a ‘plan’ record (this removes it from the Plan List page)   
    * Once the Routing event is Complete (Depart location timestamp is entered)  
    * Or an associated gate transaction is entered (a ‘plan’ record is essentially an expected gate transaction)   
      * An Inbound Plan \= Gate In transaction  
      * An Outbound Plan \= Gate Out transaction   
* In Yard Moves page , add tabs for Inbound Plan and Outbound Plan  
  * Almost exactly the same format as Gate Transactions except displays equipment with a matching Load in the TMS that has a scheduled appointment which allows us to calculate the estimated Yard arrival or departure date & time  
  * Records stay on the Plan list once created until they are Deleted or Completed

### Stacking / Grounding \- Ready

* In Yard Builder  
  * Add a place for the user input the \# of “Top Loaders” they have  
    * These aren’t physical elements like the rest of the yard, merely a quantity to track- almost like inventory that never leaves the yard.  Perhaps classify it as “Yard Equipment”    
    * Ideally, a user should be able to view & update where a Top Loader was last parked very easily- during a Yard Move or Yard Check, or perhaps from a Current Inventory page (maybe a small section for Yard Equipment location)   
* Concept of grounding/mounting and stacking/unstacking.  For reference \-    
  * Both of the following can only be done if the yard has a top loader (a piece of heavy equipment that can physically lift containers)   
  * “Stacking” is when chassis or grounding containers are stacked on top of the other to better utilize yard space.    
    * Support marking a spot as “Stacked”  
      * When this occurs, up to 5 pieces of inventory (chassis or ‘grounded containers’ only) can be assigned to the same spot location   
      * Specify stack position by assigning A/B/C/D/E with A being the lowest position in the stack.  So the full location of a container would be “\[section name\] \- \[spot \#\] \- \[stack position\]”, example “A-12-C would be section A, spot 12, 3rd position in the stack ”  
  * “Grounding” a container is when a container is lifted off its chassis and, thus, rests directly on the ground.  The chassis can be used elsewhere.  Later, a grounded container can then be ‘mounted’ onto a different chassis   
* In Current Inventory & Yard Check  
  * Provide an option for a user to mark inventory in a current spot as ‘stacked’  
  * When a user first marks a location as stacked,   
    * If only 1 chassis/container is assigned to that spot, it’s position is “A”  
    * If additional chassis/containers are assigned to that spot afterwards, they are assigned the next letter   
  * A user can manually change the position designation of a stacked chassis/container    
* In Yard moves  
  * Additional “Move Type” options:  Ground, Mount, Stack, Unstack, Flip  
    * If Equipment type \= Container, Options \= Reposition, Ground, Mount, Stack, Unstack, Flip  
    * If Equipment type \= Chassis, Options \= Reposition, Stack, Unstack  
    * If Equipment type \= Trailer, Options \= Reposition (only)  
  * Field requirements  
    * IF Type \= Ground, Mount, or Flip   
      * From & To are actually chassis values instead of location values  
      * Ground:   
        * From \= existing chassis value  
        * To \= null (and should be allowed to save as null)   
      * Mount:   
        * From \= null  
        * To \= new chassis value   
      * Flip:   
        * From \= existing chassis value  
        * To \= new chassis value   
    * IF Type \= Stack or Unstack, multiple “To” values may need to be updated.  If the container needing to be unstacked is not at the very top of the stack, a new location may need to be specified for each of the containers stacked on top of the desired container   
      * From \= current spot location   
      * To \= a new spot location (but should be allowed to save even if the location does not change)   
        * AND give user option to input new location values for all other containers in the same stack   
    * No change to Priority, Status, or Assigned To field values  
  * When creating, editing, or completing a Yard Move, the user can select a spot that already has assigned equipment  
    * If they select a spot with assigned equipment, text will appear with a checkbox (that is checked by default) which states “mark location as stacked?”  
* In Recommended Moves \- if the yard has any top loaders, create Recommended Yard Moves for the following scenarios

### Exception Management update

* Routing mismatch  
  * General logic   
    * GIVEN a Gate In Transaction is triggered  
    * AND there is a single matching Load in PortPro   
    * AND there is no matching routing event  
    * WHEN the user tries to ‘save’ the gate transaction   
    * THEN have user confirm the change they want to make to the routing   
  * Confirming the change can occur in 2 locations \-   
    * If self check in is not enabled, the routing confirmation will occur after clicking ‘complete/save’ on the Gate Transaction modal   
    * If self check in is enabled, the routing confirmation can occur in both the Driver Mobile app after they click “Arrived” and the Gate Transaction modal   
  * Routing confirmation   
    * “This equipment is not currently routed to be dropped at this yard.  Please select one of the following:   
      * Update the Drop location from \[current routed location\] to \[YMS yard location\]  
      * Add a yard stop to the routing”  
    * Options   
      * Cancel \- this takes them back to the prior page they were on (if it’s the Gate Transaction modal, keep all inputted values)   
      * Save   
        * Update the Drop location \- this will update the location of the Drop event and following Hook event to the yard location   
        * Add a yard stop \- this will add a Yard Drop event before the currently routed event   
          * Example  
            * Current routing: Pickup at APM Terminal \> Drop at Target  
            * “Add yard stop” is selected \- this becomes 2 Moves  
              * Pickup at APM Terminal \> Drop at Yard Location   
              * Hook at Yard Location \> Drop at Target  
* Chassis mismatch   
  * General logic   
    * GIVEN a Gate In Transaction is triggered  
    * AND there is a single matching Load in PortPro   
    * AND there is a chassis \# associated with the Load in PortPro  
    * WHEN the user tries to ‘save’ the gate transaction  
    * AND the chassis \# recorded is different than the chassis \# in the Load    
    * THEN have user confirm if the chassis \# should be updated  
  * Same as routing mismatch, this confirmation will occur either on the Driver Mobile app (if they are doing self check-in) or from the Gate Transaction workflow   
  * Chassis \# confirmation   
    * “The Load currently has the chassis \# recorded as \[current chassis \#\].  Please select one of the following:   
      * Update the chassis \# on the Load from \[current chassis \#\] to \[newly entered chassis \#\]  
      * Use \[current chassis \#\] for this gate transaction”   
    * Options   
      * Cancel \- this takes them back to the prior page they were on (if it’s the Gate Transaction modal, keep all inputted values)   
      * Save   
        * Update chassis \# on Load \- this will update the chassis \# on the Load based on what was inputted in the YMS  
        * Use current chassis \# for gate transaction \- no change to the Load, use the Load’s chassis \# when saving the Gate Transaction   
* For Any updates made to the Load by the YMS, be sure to add an audit event to the Load for the change and the user displayed will be “YMS \- \[username\]”
